1. Initial Setup (Registration & Exploration)
1.1 Start the Challenge:
Click Start on the Postbook challenge. This will open a new web application in your browser.

1.2 Register a New Account:
On the homepage, click Sign up. Create a new user with the credentials of your choice (for example: mytestuser / mytestpass).

1.3 Log In:
After registering, use your new credentials to log in.

1.4 Explore the Dashboard:
Once logged in, you are taken to your personal dashboard. Key areas to notice are:

Write a new post: A form to create new blog entries.

Posts: Existing public posts from other accounts (e.g., user and admin) are visible here.

Edit & Delete options: Available for your own posts.

1.5 Key Observation #1 – Cookie:
Open your browser's developer tools and navigate to the Application tab (Chrome/Edge) or Storage tab (Firefox). Under Cookies, you'll find a cookie named id with a value that looks like a hash. This is a critical finding.

1.6 Key Observation #2 – URL Structure:
When you click on a post, the URL includes the parameter page=view.php and id=N, where N is a number. Example: index.php?page=view.php&id=3.

2. Flag 0 – The user Account's Simple Password
Hint: "The person with username “user” has a very easy password"

Vulnerability: Weak password (brute‑force not required – it's just the word password).

2.1 Log Out of your current session.

2.2 Attempt to log in with the following credentials:

Username: user

Password: password

2.3 Result: You are logged in, and Flag 0 is immediately displayed on the screen.

3. Flag 1 – Accessing a Hidden Post by Altering the id Parameter
Hint: "Try viewing your own post and then see if you can change the ID"

Vulnerability: IDOR (Insecure Direct Object Reference) – the application does not verify if the user has permission to view a given post.

3.1 While logged in, create a new test post with some dummy content (do not mark it as private). After publishing, note the id value in the URL. For example: index.php?page=view.php&id=3

3.2 Change the id parameter in the address bar from 3 to 2. The URL now becomes: index.php?page=view.php&id=2

3.3 Hit Enter to load the page.

3.4 Result: You can view the post with id=2, which belongs to another user. This displays Flag 1.

4. Flag 2 – Creating a Post as Another User via Client-Side Tampering
Hint: "You should definitely use 'Inspect Element' on the form when creating a new post"

Vulnerability: Lack of server-side validation of the user_id when creating a post (client-side trust).

4.1 Navigate to the "Write a new post" form.

4.2 Open Developer Tools (F12) and inspect the HTML form. Look for an <input> field named user_id.

4.3 Change its value attribute from your current user's ID (e.g., 3) to 1.

4.4 Fill in the title and content as usual and submit the form.

4.5 Result: The post is created as if it were submitted by user_id = 1, which corresponds to the admin user. Flag 2 is displayed.

5. Flag 3 – The ID 945 (189 * 5)
Hint: *"189 * 5"*

Vulnerability: Predictable ID enumeration.

5.1 Multiply 189 by 5 to get the number 945.

5.2 In the address bar, navigate to: index.php?page=view.php&id=945

5.3 Result: The page loads a post and reveals Flag 3.

6. Flag 4 – Editing Someone Else's Post
Hint: "You can edit your own posts, what about someone else’s?"

Vulnerability: IDOR in the edit function.

6.1 From your dashboard, click the "Edit" button next to one of your own posts. Take note of the URL: index.php?page=edit.php&id=3 (the number will vary).

6.2 Change the id parameter in the address bar to 2.

6.3 You are now on the edit page of the post belonging to another user. Make a trivial change (e.g., add a space) and click Save.

6.4 Result: The application allows you to edit and save the post, and Flag 4 is displayed.

7. Flag 5 – Hijacking the user Account via MD5 Cookies
Hint: "The cookie allows you to stay signed in. Can you figure out how they work so you can sign in to user with ID 1?"

Vulnerability: Predictable cookie generation using MD5 hashes.

7.1 Check your current id cookie in Developer Tools → Application → Cookies. The value will be something like c81e728d9d4c2f636f067f89cc14862c.

7.2 Use an online MD5 reverse lookup tool (e.g., md5.gromweb.com) to see what number this hash corresponds to. You will find that the hash represents the number 2.

7.3 Calculate the MD5 hash of the number 1 using an online tool, the command line (echo -n 1 | md5sum), or a scripting language.

7.4 Replace your current cookie value with this new MD5 hash (of the number 1).

7.5 Refresh the page. The application will now believe you are the user with id = 1 (the admin account), and Flag 5 will appear.

8. Flag 6 – Deleting a Post with MD5 ID Values
Hint: "Deleting a post seems to take an ID that is not a number. Can you figure out what it is?"

Vulnerability: IDOR in the delete function, using MD5 hashes for IDs.

8.1 From your dashboard, click the "Delete" button next to one of your posts. Observe the URL: index.php?page=delete.php&id=MD5_HASH_VALUE.

8.2 The id value is not a plain number; it's an MD5 hash. Determine which post ID it corresponds to by using an MD5 reverse lookup tool, or by hashing a few small integers (1, 2, 3, 4...) until you get a match.

8.3 Once you know the mapping, generate the MD5 hash of the target post ID you want to delete (for example, the one belonging to another user).

8.4 Modify the URL by replacing the id parameter value with this new hash.

8.5 Press Enter. The other user's post will be deleted, and Flag 6 will be displayed.

